{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7fbbb7eb-9168-4267-bb2d-166586c22383","content":"The repo appears empty, so I'll answer from general .NET/NativeAOT knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n\n2. **Reproduce the crash** — macOS will write a Mach-O core file to the path above.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/` as well** — by default macOS may place cores in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to inspect the dump**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **Load the SOS/dotnet debugging plugin** (if available for NativeAOT):\n   ```\n   (lldb) plugin load libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n\n6. **Check Console.app / crash reports** — macOS also writes `.ips` crash reports to `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`. These contain stack traces and can be useful even without a full core dump.\n\n**Key gotchas:**\n- **SIP (System Integrity Protection)** can block core dump generation for system-protected paths. Use a custom `kern.corefile` path.\n- NativeAOT binaries don't ship `createdump`, so the OS-level core dump is your primary option.\n- Ensure the binary has debug symbols (publish with `-p:StripSymbols=false`) for meaningful stack traces in `lldb`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"04f0c9da-2c41-4e19-8f1b-a3f6a8253140","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository is empty. This is a general knowledge question about macOS crash dump recovery for NativeAOT apps. Let me answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":438},"id":"ebc51f3e-9f94-4200-ad75-4a8dd9a95a5e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:05:51.525Z","parentId":"c0e60dd8-0bd0-40e5-a5b9-9cbd6de071e5"}
